items.items: Blood cell count and differential finding
Relative and absolute amounts of blood cells identified within an identified specimen.
For example: whole blood; urine; or CSF.
Red cell count (RCC)
Total number of erythrocytes per volume unit of the specimen.
White cell count (WCC)
Total number of leucocytes per volume unit of the specimen.
Lymphocyte count
Number of lymphocytes per volume unit of the specimen.
Neutrophil count
Number of neutrophils per volume unit of the specimen.
Eosinophil count
Number of eosinophils per volume unit of the specimen.
Basophil count
Number of basophils per volume unit of the specimen.
Monocyte count
Number of monocytes per volume unit of the specimen.
Platelet count
Number of platelets per volume unit of the specimen.
Blast count
Number of blast cells per volume unit of the specimen.
Specimen
Identification of the specimen examined.

Most commonly, the specimen analysed is blood, as part of a complete blood count (or full blood examination) but other body fluids, such as cerebrospinal fluid or urine, may also be tested to identify and quantify the blood cells present. If the tissue specimen has previously been identified in a a higher level archetype level archetype, such as the OBSERVATION.laboratory_test_result, this SLOT may be redundant.
Most often, the specimen is blood, but other body fluids like cerebrospinal fluid or urine can also be analyzed to identify and quantify the blood cells present.
Typically, the sample used is blood, but other body fluids like cerebrospinal fluid or urine may also be tested to identify and count the blood cells present.
Comment
Additional narrative about the blood cell count, not captured in other fields.
Neutrophil %
The proportion of neutrophils compared to the total white blood cell count.
Lymphocyte %
The proportion of lymphocytes compared to the total white blood cell count.
Monocyte %
The proportion of monocytes compared to the total white blood cell count.
Eosinophil %
The proportion of eosinophils compared to the white blood cell count.
Basophil %
The proportion of basophils observed compared to the total white blood cell count.
Blast %
The proportion of blast cells compared to the total white blood cell count.
